== Early Life ==
'''Fran<U+00E9> Lessac''' grew up in [[New Jersey]] and was influenced by weekends spent exploring the artistic and cultural milieu of [[New York]] city. As a teenager Lessac moved to [[California]] to study film, and then in 1978 to the Caribbean island of [[Montserrat]], which was to become the subject of her first children's book, ''My Little Island'' in 1984. The bright colors and patterns of the old-style West Indian architecture and culture of [[Montserrat]] proved to be a continuing influence in many of Lessac's subsequent books, and [[Na<U+00EF>ve art]] style paintings. <ref>http://www.franelessac.com/aboutfrane.htm</ref>

== Career ==
After ''My Little Island'', Lessac went on to publish a number of children's books, initially in the U.K, the U.S and later in Australia where she relocated with her husband, author and musician, Mark Greenwood. <ref>http://www.love2read.org.au/featured-ambassador-week9-frane.cfm</ref> Her first book, ''My Little Island'', was named Children's Book of the Year by the St Martins Children's Book Council and also became a feature book on the popular U.S television program [[Reading Rainbow]]. In 2002 Lessac won the [[Western Australian Premier's Book Awards]] for ''The Legend of [[Moondyne Joe]]''<ref>http://pba.slwa.wa.gov.au/awards_archive/2002</ref> was nominated as an Honor book in the [[Children's Book of the Year Award: Eve Pownall Award for Information Books]] <ref>http://cbca.org.au/winners2009.htm</ref> for ''Simpson and his Donkey'' both of which were written by her husband and frequent collaborator, Mark Greenwood.
In 2002 Fran<U+00E9> Lessac founded a Western Australian Branch of the [[Society of Children's Book Writers and Illustrators]].<ref>http://www.scbwiaustralia.org/scbwi-leadership-team.php</ref> She is also on the Executive Committee of the [[Australian Society of Authors]]. <ref>http://www.writingwa.org/articles/ASA</ref> For her contribution to children's literature in Western Australia Lessac was awarded the 2010 Muriel Barwell Award by The [[Children's Book Council of Australia]] WA Branch. <ref>http://wa.cbca.org.au/wabarwell.htm</ref>

